# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: batchoy-tagalog
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:batchoy-tagalog/15-bean-soup] This is a **list of notable bean soups** characterized by soups that use beans as a primary ingredient.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/a-gei] The ageh was reportedly created in 1965 by Iông-tēⁿ Gím-bûn (楊鄭錦文), who combined various food items sold at her Chin-lí street (真理街) food stall to sell as a new food item.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/a-gei] This original ageh consisted of fried tofu that has been emptied of its center, stuffed with cellophane noodles cooked in stewed ground pork, its opening sealed and covered with a carrot and surimi mixture, and then steamed to completion.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/a-gei] The dish incorporates several techniques from other dishes, including the stuffing of abura-age in the manner of *inarizushi*, the capping of tofu with surimi to make Yong Tau Foo, and the use of cellophane noodles as a filling for many stuffed pastries.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/a-gei] The individual a-gei are served with either a plain soy-based or a sweet chili sauce.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/a-gei] A-gei is commonly eaten with a bowl of stuffed fish ball soup in the winter and a glass of cold soy milk in the summer.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/aburasoba] Mazesoba was introduced in the 1950s, with Chinchintei opening up in Musashino City in the 1950s.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/aburasoba] The largest aburasoba chain in the world is Kokoro Mazesoba.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/aburasoba] There are two theories about its origin: one is that Sanko, a restaurant near Hitotsubashi University in Kunitachi City, founded in 1952, started serving it as a snack with alcohol.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/aburasoba] They were likely inspired in the 1950s by soggy ramen noodles.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/aburasoba] The other theory is that Chinchintei, a restaurant near Asia University in the Musashino City district, started selling aburasoba in the 1950s.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/aburasoba] It became popular and ranked in the Shimbun list of Trending Products of the Year.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/aburasoba] In 2002, Myojo Foods launched the "Bubukka" oil-based instant noodles in Kichijoji, Musashino City.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/aburasoba] It is said that it became popular among students because of its relatively low price and large portions.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/aburasoba] According to Great Gidayu, after entering Asia University, a senior student took him to a restaurant that served *aburasoba* as a "rite of passage".
[src:batchoy-tagalog/aburasoba] Although he didn't think it tasted good at first, he became addicted after going there several times.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/aburasoba] Chinchintei sells noodles, soup, and more by mail order, but most of the orders are from alumni of Asia University.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/aburasoba] It has also become a specialty menu item at some student cafeterias.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/afang-soup] The ingredients used to prepare afang soup include beef, fish (dried and stock), palm oil, crayfish, pepper, kpomo, shaki (cow tripe), waterleaf, afang leaf, onion, periwinkle, salt, and seasonings.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/afang-soup] Add crayfish and pepper to meat stock and boil it.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/afang-soup] Add grounded okazi to the beef stock and cook it.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/afang-soup] Then heat up the oil in a separate pot and add chopped onions for about a minute.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/afang-soup] Add stock fish, dried fish, and other prepared meats like beef, ponmo and shaki to the pot.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/afang-soup] Taste for seasoning, stir, and adjust as necessary.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/afang-soup] Then, add the afang leaf , stir to combine, reduce the heat to simmer for an additional two minutes, and then turn off the heat.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/afritada] The name *afritada* is derived from Spanish *fritada* ("fried"), referring to the first step of the preparation in which the meat is pan-fried before simmering in the tomato sauce.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/afritada] Filipino *menudo* and *kaldereta* both use tomato sauce or banana ketchup.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/afritada] However, *menudo* includes sliced liver, while *kaldereta* exclusively uses goat meat or occasionally beef.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/afritada] *Igado* contains liver but no tomato sauce.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour dishes, sauces, and cooking methods have a long history in China.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] One of the earliest recordings of sweet and sour may come from *Shaowei Yanshi Dan* (Chinese: 燒尾宴食單; pinyin: *shāowěi yànshí dān*), a menu of the food served in Tang dynasty (618–907) "Shaowei banquet" festivals written in 708.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] It included many sweet and sour adjacent dishes and recorded that they were invented by Chancellor Wei Juyuan under Emperor Zhongzong of Tang when he hosted the Emperor at his house.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Some authors say that the original sweet and sour sauce (Chinese: 糖醋醬; pinyin: *tángcùjiàng*) came from the Chinese province of Henan, but the sauce in this area is a light vinegar and sugar mixture not resembling what most people, including the Chinese, would call sweet and sour.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Many places in China use a sweet and sour sauce as a dipping sauce for fish and meat rather than in cooking, as is common in Westernized Chinese cuisine.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] This style of using sauces is popular amongst Chinese who tie certain sauces to particular meats such as chili and soy for shrimp and vinegar and garlic for goose.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] There are, however, some dishes, such as the Cantonese sweet and sour pork or loong har kow (sweet and sour lobster balls), in which the meat is cooked and a sauce added to the wok before serving.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Not all dishes are cooked; some, such as "sweet and sour fruit and vegetable" salad from the eastern regions of China, also find their way in Chinese cuisine.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] This cold dish combines salad vegetables such as cucumber, tomato, bell pepper, and onion with a mixture of pineapple (or pear), vinegar, and sugar.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] In China, the sauces are traditionally made by mixing sugar or honey with a sour liquid such as rice vinegar or soy sauce and spices such as ginger and cloves.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Sometimes a paste made from tomatoes is used, but this is rare and normally restricted to Western cooking.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Cantonese sweet and sour sauce is the direct ancestor of the sauce of the same name in the West and was originally developed for sweet and sour pork.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] The late Hong Kong chef Leung King included the following as his sweet and sour sauce recipe: white rice vinegar, salt, Chinese brown candy, ketchup, Worcestershire sauce, and dark soy sauce.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] He suggests the more acidic white rice vinegar could be replaced with apple cider vinegar and that ketchup and Worcestershire sauce should be of renowned gourmet brands.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] The original Cantonese sweet and sour pork (traditional Chinese: 咕嚕肉; simplified Chinese: 咕噜肉; pinyin: *gūlūròu*; Cantonese Yale: *gūlōuyuhk*; lit.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] 'rumbling meat') is made with vinegar, preserved plums and hawthorn candy for an almost scarlet color and sweet-sour taste.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] A related Hong Kong/Cantonese-based dish is sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 生炒排骨; pinyin: *Shēngchǎo páigǔ*; Cantonese Yale: *sāangcháau pàaigwāt*; lit.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] The methods used are identical, with spareribs used instead of pork loin.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] A similar dish is gu lao rou or sweet and sour pork.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Originating in Suzhou, Jiangsu province, the squirrel-shaped Mandarin fish (Chinese: 松鼠鱖魚; pinyin: *Sōngshǔ Guìyú*) has a crisp skin but soft center.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] The fish body of *Siniperca chuatsi* is scored such that it fans out when cooked, similar in appearance to a bushy squirrel tail.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] The fish is served with a sweet and sour sauce drizzled on top and garnished with a little shrimp meat and dried bamboo shoots.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] A specialty of Shandong province, in particular the city of Jinan, the Yellow River carp is prepared by making diagonal slices partway through its flesh.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] It is next coated in corn flour, then deep-fried, causing the fish to curl and the slices to open out.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Finally, a sweet and sour sauce is poured over the cooked fish.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] This is one of the distinctive dishes typical of Shandong cuisine.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] A popular dish in Shanghai cuisine, sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 糖醋小排; pinyin: *tángcù xiǎopái*) are made using pork ribs that are lightly coated in cornstarch and seasoned before being fried and served in a sweet and sour sauce.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] In South Korea, a sweet and sour meat dish known as *tangsuyuk* (탕수육; 糖水肉) is one of the most popular Korean Chinese dishes.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Made with either pork or beef, the bite-sized pieces are usually coated with potato/sweet potato starch/cornstarch or glutinous rice flour and double-fried in oil.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] The dish is served with sweet and sour sauce, typically made by boiling vinegar, sugar, and water with a variety of fruits and vegetables like carrot, cucumber, onion, wood ear mushroom, and pineapple.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Starch slurry is used to thicken the sauce.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] The traditional Dalmatian dish Pašticada features prunes and sweet dessert wine (prošek) as the sweet components, and vinegar in the marinade for sourness.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour sauces have been used in English cuisine since the Middle Ages, with recipes for sweet and sour meat and fish in the 1390 cookery book *The Forme of Cury*.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, a sweet and sour sauce base made from sugar and vinegar is a gastrique.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] *Aigre-doux* is a sweet and sour sauce in general.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] According to food writer Arthur Schwartz, within Neapolitan cooking, sweet and sour was the dominant food pairing before the introduction of the tomato and the mass-uptake of pasta.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Preparations using the combination eaten in the modern cuisine include sweet and sour eggplant, but it is never used to flavour pasta dishes.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] In Filipino cuisine, sweet and sour sauces are known as **agre dulce** or **Filipino sweet and sour sauce**.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] They are made by mixing cornstarch with water, salt, sugar, and a tangy ingredient (typically tomato ketchup, banana ketchup, or pineapples).
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] The mixture is brought to a boil then simmered until it thickens.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] The name means "sour-sweet" in Philippine Spanish, from Spanish *agrio* ("sour") and *dulce* ("sweet").
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] It is also known as *agri dulci* in Chavacano and the phrase can refer to dishes cooked with the sauce.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] *Agre dulce* is commonly used as a dipping sauce for appetizers like *lumpia* or *okoy*.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour chicken is a dish frequently served in Chinese restaurants in various countries in Oceania, Europe, North America, and South America and available at some restaurants in East Asia and Southeast Asia in an essentially identical version.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] The dish generally comprises cubes of white meat chicken deep-fried in batter and served with sweet and sour sauce.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Sometimes it is topped with pineapple, green pepper, carrot, or sweet pickles.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour pork is a Chinese dish particularly popular in Westernized Cantonese cuisine and may be found worldwide.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Several provinces in China produce various dishes that claim to be the ancestor, including a traditional Jiangsu dish called "pork in a sugar and vinegar sauce" (糖醋里脊; pinyin: táng cù lǐjǐ).
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] The dish consists of deep-fried pork cut into bite-sized pieces and subsequently stir-fried in a more customized version of sweet and sour sauce made of sugar, ketchup, white vinegar, and soy sauce and additional ingredients including pineapple, green pepper (capsicum), and onion.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] In more elaborate preparations, the dish's tartness is controlled by requiring that Chinese white rice vinegar be used sparingly and using ketchups with less vinegary tastes, while some restaurants use unripe kiwifruits and HP sauce in place of vinegar.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Western cultures use sweet and sour sauce in two different ways.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Dishes can either include the sauce as an ingredient in cooking or use the sauce as a pour-over or dipping sauce for the meal.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Chinese restaurants in Western countries commonly serve battered and deep-fried chicken, pork, or shrimp with a sweet and sour sauce poured on top.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] It is also common to find the sweet and sour sauce cooked with sliced green peppers, onions, and pineapple before it is poured over the meat.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Many Western dishes involve cooking the meat with a variety of ingredients to make a complete sweet and sour dish in the manner of gu lo yuk.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] The most popular dishes are those of pork and shrimp.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, it has been developed contrary to traditional French cooking practices, and the preparation of sweet and sour sauce (Aigre-douce) often involves immersing the food in a plentiful amount of sauce.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Common in Western sweet and sour sauce is the addition of fruits such as pineapple and vegetables such as sweet pepper and green onions.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Traditional rice vinegar is becoming more readily available due to the increase in Asian food stores but a mixture of vinegar and dry sherry is often still used in sweet and sour dishes.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Also common is the use of cornstarch as a thickener for the sauce and tomato ketchup to give a stronger red color to the dish and to add a Western taste.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Most supermarkets across Europe and North America carry a range of prepared sweet and sour sauces for adding to stir-fry or dipping.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Primarily in North America, sweet and sour sauce is available as a dipping sauce at Chinese takeout establishments in small plastic packets or containers.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] In Britain, Thai-style sweet chili sauce has recently overtaken the previous popularity of Chinese-style sweet and sour sauce to the extent it can often be found at non-Asian establishments for a wide variety of Western-style snacks from fishcakes to chips and seafood such as calamari and prawns.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] A number of variations are used in barbecue cuisine, either homemade or prepared from a number of common brands.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] Besides American Chinese restaurants, popular fast food restaurants such as McDonald's, Burger King, and Wendy's carry their own proprietary brands of sweet and sour sauce packets.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/agre-dulce] These are commonly offered and used as a dipping sauce for chicken fingers and chicken nuggets.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/batchoy-tagalog] Varieties of *batchoy Tagalog* depend on the household's preference or accustomed way of cooking.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/batchoy-tagalog] Aside from misua, sotanghon is another commonly used noodle in the soup.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/batchoy-tagalog] A variation of batchoy without pork blood or without noodles is also common in the localities.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/batchoy-tagalog] One of the distinctive versions of batchoy Tagalog is the comfort soup named *Bombay*, or *Bumbay*, from the province of Quezon.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/batchoy-tagalog] The name depicts the turban worn by Indians who came to the local communities many years ago.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/batchoy-tagalog] The dish is made with a mixture of ingredients, such as ground pork, pork offal, and other seasonings, which are customarily assembled in a banana leaf pouch shaped like a turban and then simmered.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/batchoy-tagalog] Mushrooms, corn, and sweet potato shoots are may also added to the dish.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/batchoy-tagalog] It is then poured with a flavorful broth.
[src:batchoy-tagalog/batchoy-tagalog] This soup is usually eaten with steamed rice.
